docs.text: based on the life story of david helfgott , this australian film is a rich exploration of the pressures drilling in upon a child-genius , compounded by the looming shadow of a domineering father .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in the 1950's helfgott emerged as a child prodigy .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the film traces his relationship with his father , whose encouragement comes at the cost of demanding david have no life beyond that of the black and white keys .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: david is offered places in the usa , but his father refuses to let him leave australia .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the effect this has upon helfgott is cleverly told via a single reverse tracked shot ; david is sobbing on the front doorway of his music teacher's house .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: he is well lit via the external house lights .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his teacher isn't home .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: we pull back and see that the dark front room's window has it's curtains open .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: there , in a pool of blackness , is a grand piano .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: david's fall over the dark cliff has begun .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: instead of being told in a linear mode , shine jumps around in time , ala " pulp fiction " .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this narrative device works well ; we see david as a boy , teenager in london and mental-patient in various snippets .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the film then neatly loops back for its uplifting conclusion .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: adult-helfgott's return to the light is told in linear fashion .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the lead role is played by 3 different actors , with the teenage-david ( taylor ) and adult-david ( rush ) standing out .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: whilst rush is known for his tv work in australia , i think this is his first major cinema work .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his david , whilst clearly damaged - he keeps quoting his " daddy " in a babbling word torrent , cuddles strangers and grabs women on the breasts - is both touching and funny .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: taylor's teenage-david is the more sympathy producing role .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: we are mute witness to his gradual breakdown as the pressures just keep on building .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: his father wants him to play the very demanding rachmaninov's 3rd , whilst his teacher wants to start him with a simple mozart .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: technically this is a beautiful film and a lot of thought has gone in to the production .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i particularly like the use of slow motion and sound effects .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: one scene has adult-helfgott happily babbling in a car in the rain .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the sound of the windshield wipers fades up over his voice .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: with a clever subtlety , the wiper sound appears to morph into a rhythmic thumping , but of the same beat .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the image dissolves and we realise the thumping is the slow motion applause of a crowd .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but it's us being clapped .

docs.text: the music , as you would expect from a film of this subject matter , is critical .

docs.text: and it works very well .

docs.text: the 'miming' of the actors piano playing is faultless ( apparently rush didn't mime ; he really did play )

docs.text: helfgott's life is certainly not without it's sympathetic people .

docs.text: indeed his return to the 'normal' world is accelerated by his chance meetings with two very special women .
